Capturing a 360-degree view of all the lights emitted from the vacuum spatial would require a very specialized type of telescope
known as an all-sky telescope. This type of telescope typically has a very wide field of view and a curved focal plane that allows it
to capture images of the entire sky at once.
To design an all-sky telescope for this purpose, you would need to consider several requirements, including:

 Step 1) Spatial resolution: The telescope would need to be able to capture fine details in the light emitted from the vacuum spatial.
         This would likely require a high spatial resolution, which would in turn require a large aperture and a high-quality optical system.

 Step 2) Sensitivity: The telescope would need to be sensitive enough to detect very faint light sources.
         This would require a detector with a high quantum efficiency and low noise, as well as careful control of stray light.

 Step 3) Field of view: The telescope would need to have a very wide field of view to capture the entire sky at once.
         This would likely require a curved focal plane and specialized optics to correct for distortions.
 
 Step 4) Spectral range: Depending on the characteristics of the light emitted from the vacuum spatial,
         the telescope may need to be able to capture light across a wide spectral range. This would require a detector with a
         broad spectral response and specialized filters or dispersive elements in the optical system.

 Step 5) Data handling and storage: Capturing a 360-degree view of the sky would generate a large amount of data,
         so the telescope would need to be able to handle and store this data efficiently. This would likely require 
         specialized electronics and software for data acquisition, processing and storage.

Defining these requirements would help guide the design of the all-sky telescope and ensure that it meets the needs of the intended 
application.

Data handling and storage: Capturing a 360-degree view of the sky would generate a large amount of data, so the telescope would need to be able
to handle and store this data efficiently. This would likely require specialized electronics and software for data acquisition, processing,and storage.
The purpose is make one real-time share of all views and one little storage to don't loss any data and not fully the space of storage very easy
Capturing a 360-degree view of the sky using an all-sky telescope would generate a large amount of data that needs to be handled and stored
efficiently. One possible approach to handle and share this data in real-time is to use a distributed data processing and storage system,
such as Apache Kafka and Apache Cassandra.

Apache Kafka is a distributed streaming platform that can handle large amounts of real-time data streams and enables high-throughput, 
low-latency data processing. It can act as a data broker that receives, stores, and distributes data between different applications, services,
and systems. The data captured by the all-sky telescope can be streamed to Kafka in real-time, where it can be partitioned,
replicated, and processed by multiple consumers.

Apache Cassandra is a distributed NoSQL database that can store and manage large volumes of data across multiple nodes.
It is highly scalable, fault-tolerant, and provides high-performance read and write operations.
The data processed by Kafka can be stored in Cassandra in real-time, where it can be indexed, queried, and analyzed by multiple users and applications.

To use Apache Kafka and Apache Cassandra for real-time data sharing and storage, you would need to set up and configure the following components:
  1) Kafka producer: This component would be responsible for capturing and sending the data from the all-sky telescope to Kafka in real-time.
  2) Kafka broker: This component would receive, store, and distribute the data streams from the Kafka producer to multiple Kafka consumers.
  3) Kafka consumer: These components would process and analyze the data streams from Kafka and perform real-time data processing, visualization,
     and alerting.
  4) Cassandra cluster: This cluster would store and manage the data processed by Kafka and enable real-time querying, indexing, and analysis.
  5) Data processing and visualization tools: These tools would be used to process, analyze, and visualize the real-time data captured by
     the all-sky telescope and stored in Cassandra.
     
By using a distributed data processing and storage system such as Apache Kafka and Apache Cassandra,
you can handle and share the real-time data generated by the all-sky telescope efficiently and enable multiple users and applications to access
and analyze the data simultaneously.

